        <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Used Car Loan Rates in Australia (2026)</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Used car loan rates are slightly higher than new car rates because older vehicles depreciate faster, carry more mechanical risk, and provide less security value to lenders. Rates for used cars in early 2026 typically range from 5.49% to 12% p.a. depending on the vehicle age, your credit profile, and whether the loan is secured.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Many lenders have tiered rates based on vehicle age: vehicles under 3 years old often qualify for near-new-car rates, 3–5 years old attract moderate increases, 5–7 years old see further increases, and vehicles over 7–10 years may not qualify for secured finance at all with some lenders. The lowest secured rate available is 4.99% from Firefighters Credit Union.</p>
        <div class="bg-[#0d4d3e]/5 border-l-4 border-[#10b981] rounded-r-lg p-6 my-6"><p class="text-[#0d4d3e] font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">Some lenders have no maximum vehicle age for secured loans, while others cut off at 7, 10, or 12 years old at the end of the loan term. If you are buying an older used car, your choice of lender matters enormously. Nik Finance identifies which lenders from our 130+ panel will finance your specific vehicle.</p></div>
        </section>
        <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Buying a Used Car: Dealer vs Private Sale</h2>
        <h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-xl text-[#0d4d3e] mt-8 mb-4">Dealer Purchase</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Dealer purchases are simpler for finance — the lender pays the dealer directly, and the dealer handles transfer paperwork. You may also have consumer warranty protections depending on the state. However, dealer prices are typically higher than private sale, and dealers may push their own finance at marked-up rates.</p>
        <h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-xl text-[#0d4d3e] mt-8 mb-4">Private Sale</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Private sales often offer better purchase prices but require more due diligence. For finance, most lenders require a PPSR check (to confirm no existing finance on the vehicle), a current market valuation (such as RedBook or Glass's Guide), vehicle inspection, and the seller's details. Pre-approval is especially valuable for private sales because it lets you act quickly — sellers prefer buyers who can settle immediately.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">What to Check Before Financing a Used Car</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-3 my-6">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">PPSR check — $2 search confirms no existing finance, stolen status, or write-off history. Essential for private sales.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Independent inspection — a pre-purchase inspection by a qualified mechanic costs $150–$300 and can save you thousands in hidden problems.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Service history — regular servicing documented in the logbook shows the vehicle has been maintained properly.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Km vs age — high kilometres for the age may indicate harder use and faster wear. Low kilometres on an old car may indicate long periods of sitting idle.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Insurance — comprehensive insurance is usually required for secured loans. Get a quote before committing — some older or modified vehicles carry high premiums.</span></li>
          </ul>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Nik Finance can help you assess whether the vehicle you are considering meets lender criteria before you commit to a purchase.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Used Car Loan Features</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-3 my-6">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Secured rates from 4.99% p.a. for newer used vehicles with strong credit</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Loan terms 1–7 years — shorter terms recommended for older vehicles to avoid owing more than the car is worth</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Finance amounts typically $5,000 to $75,000 for used vehicles</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Many lenders allow private sale purchases — not just dealer</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">Some lenders include on-road costs in the loan amount</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3"><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg><span class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light">No deposit options available for used cars with good credit</span></li>
          </ul>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The average used car loan amount in Australia is lower than new, typically $15,000–$30,000, which means even small rate differences have a smaller absolute dollar impact. Focus on the comparison rate and total cost rather than chasing the lowest headline rate.</p>
